00:13:39.160 --> 00:13:42.970
that were suffering from pretty
substantial cost overruns

00:13:42.970 --> 00:13:44.270
and time delays.

00:13:44.270 --> 00:13:47.510
It's easier now to say that
we have a better handle

00:13:47.510 --> 00:13:51.560 position:56%
on our acquisition programs
because we have a lot fewer of them,

00:13:51.560 --> 00:13:53.120
and so they're easier to oversee.

00:13:53.120 --> 00:13:57.070
But we've made a lot of changes
to the acquisition process.

00:13:57.070 --> 00:13:59.600
If I had more time that
would be a primary focus

00:13:59.600 --> 00:14:00.900
to keep working on that.

00:14:00.900 --> 00:14:05.280
And a bit part of it's not just
changing what we do internally.

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:08.400
It is changing how we interact
with, and collaborate with,

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:13.250
work with those outside
the Department of Defense.

00:14:13.250 --> 00:14:18.000
Technology is -- companies
and academic centers --

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.990
that they develop technology is a
different way than they used to.

00:14:20.990 --> 00:14:24.850
It's very iterative now and we
aren't generally agile enough

00:14:24.850 --> 00:14:26.650 position:56%
to even keep up with that iteration.

00:14:26.650 --> 00:14:27.950
I mean we all now have --

00:14:27.950 --> 00:14:30.150
we're probably the last
people institutionally to hold

00:14:30.150 --> 00:14:33.590
on to BlackBerrys because Apple
didn't want to work with us.

00:14:33.590 --> 00:14:36.410
They said, you know, we put -- the
product is just one part of it.

00:14:36.410 --> 00:14:38.980
The software, the updates, it all
is a package that goes together,

00:14:38.980 --> 00:14:42.980
and you are not equipped
to receive our technology

00:14:42.980 --> 00:14:44.510
and we just can't be bothered.

00:14:44.510 --> 00:14:47.190
And so I think that's
a cautionary tale

00:14:47.190 --> 00:14:50.590
for how we build, acquire things.

00:14:50.590 --> 00:14:52.440
I think there's more we can
be getting off the shelf

00:14:52.440 --> 00:14:54.220
and getting a [inaudible] faster.

00:14:54.220 --> 00:14:57.210
But also about how we build
and acquire larger things.

00:14:57.210 --> 00:14:59.390 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: I'd like to give
you an opportunity to talk about one

00:14:59.390 --> 00:15:03.460
of your major achievements as
Secretary which is standing

00:15:03.460 --> 00:15:06.250
up the Rapid Capabilities
Office in the Army.

00:15:06.250 --> 00:15:09.510
Can you tell everybody what
that is, what the structure is,

00:15:09.510 --> 00:15:13.840
what goals you're hoping to achieve
with it, and why it's so important

00:15:13.840 --> 00:15:16.040
to create -- give the
Army the ability

00:15:16.040 --> 00:15:19.500
to create disruptive technologies
in the short amount of time?

00:15:19.500 --> 00:15:20.880
&gt;&gt; Eric Fanning: So
there are a lot of --

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:23.390
you know, I say is there's
actually a lot of creativity

00:15:23.390 --> 00:15:25.380
and innovation inside the
Department of Defense --

00:15:25.380 --> 00:15:27.920
in uniform, in civilian workforce,

00:15:27.920 --> 00:15:30.150
among our traditional
industrial base.

00:15:30.150 --> 00:15:33.390
There's a lot of creativity
despite the barriers we've put

00:15:33.390 --> 00:15:35.560
up in their -- in place of them.

00:15:35.560 --> 00:15:38.350
So the Rapid Capabilities
Office really was --

00:15:38.350 --> 00:15:41.370
in my job in the Air Force as
the Air Force Undersecretary,

00:15:41.370 --> 00:15:43.790
which is the Number
Two, a lot of work

00:15:43.790 --> 00:15:45.730
with the Air Force Rapid
Capabilities Office,

00:15:45.730 --> 00:15:48.540
which is an enormous
organization because of all

00:15:48.540 --> 00:15:52.580
of the black world programs
that are parked in the Air Force

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:54.240
and moved through this office.

00:15:54.240 --> 00:15:58.400
The Army's version is
different and really was built

00:15:58.400 --> 00:16:05.520
on what we were seeing, really
what we were seeing the Russians do

00:16:05.520 --> 00:16:10.190 position:56%
with Ukraine and realizing that they
had been watching us more closely

00:16:10.190 --> 00:16:13.450
than maybe we'd been watching them,
that they had turned into a more

00:16:13.450 --> 00:16:17.070
of a learning organization than
they had been during the Cold War,

00:16:17.070 --> 00:16:19.680
and that the decisive edge we won

00:16:19.680 --> 00:16:24.810
in capability maybe wasn't
what we had tracked it to be.

00:16:24.810 --> 00:16:28.770
And so the way I describe our
Rapid Capabilities Office,

00:16:28.770 --> 00:16:31.010
and nobody's allowed
to call it the RCO --

00:16:31.010 --> 00:16:32.880
we're drawing a line at Acronyms

00:16:32.880 --> 00:16:38.130
with the Rapid Capabilities Office
-- is that it fills a gap in time.

00:16:38.130 --> 00:16:40.510
And I use a helicopter
as an example.

00:16:40.510 --> 00:16:43.420 position:56%
We're not going to enlarge the Rapid
Capabilities Office to something

00:16:43.420 --> 00:16:45.580 position:56%
that can build an entire helicopter.

00:16:45.580 --> 00:16:50.650
But there might be some capability
on that helicopter that we need

00:16:50.650 --> 00:16:53.360
to pull out and accelerate
to field it faster

00:16:53.360 --> 00:16:55.240
for the existing fleet
that we've got.

00:16:55.240 --> 00:16:57.810 position:56%
And so we're really looking at a one

00:16:57.810 --> 00:17:02.180
to five year time horizon
to plug gaps.

00:17:02.180 --> 00:17:05.780
And I don't know -- in some cases
they're gaps and some places it's

00:17:05.780 --> 00:17:09.000
to get that decisive
edge back in capability.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:10.300
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Right.

00:17:10.300 --> 00:17:11.600
&gt;&gt; Eric Fanning: And if
it's aligned right --

00:17:11.600 --> 00:17:12.900
it's not meant to be a workaround

00:17:12.900 --> 00:17:14.610
to the big existing
acquisition process.

00:17:14.610 --> 00:17:16.030
We still need to keep
working on that.

00:17:16.030 --> 00:17:19.740
But if these things are aligned
right, then the technology

00:17:19.740 --> 00:17:22.220
and capability we can get out in
the Rapid Capabilities Office will

00:17:22.220 --> 00:17:25.390
inform the more strategic
modernization that's taking place

00:17:25.390 --> 00:17:26.690
over a longer term.

00:17:26.690 --> 00:17:28.400
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: So it's a
building block in other words.

00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:30.330
&gt;&gt; Eric Fanning: It's
a building block, yeah.

00:17:30.330 --> 00:17:35.560 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Due to frequent
deployments and repeated deployments

00:17:35.560 --> 00:17:38.090 position:56%
because of the global war on terror,

00:17:38.090 --> 00:17:41.220
many service members
have come back obviously

00:17:41.220 --> 00:17:46.070
with severe physical injuries,
but also have returned

00:17:46.070 --> 00:17:50.950
with what is sometimes
called "invisible injuries,"

00:17:50.950 --> 00:17:54.240
post-traumatic stress
disorder, depression.

00:17:54.240 --> 00:17:59.090
The Army has endured for the
past several years an elevated

00:17:59.090 --> 00:18:00.650
suicide rate.

00:18:00.650 --> 00:18:01.950
Can you talk about that?

00:18:01.950 --> 00:18:05.140 position:56%
And what are the things that are
being put in place right now in Army

00:18:05.140 --> 00:18:07.590
to try to solve that problem?

00:18:07.590 --> 00:18:10.920
And are they addressing
the underlying problems

00:18:10.920 --> 00:18:12.570
of culture and stigma?

00:18:12.570 --> 00:18:14.120
&gt;&gt; Eric Fanning: So there's --

00:18:14.120 --> 00:18:18.310
you know, I think there's a lot
of work being doing in this area.

00:18:18.310 --> 00:18:19.880
There's a lot of focus on it.

00:18:19.880 --> 00:18:21.180
There's a lot of attention on it.

00:18:21.180 --> 00:18:22.950
There's a great deal
more to be done.

00:18:22.950 --> 00:18:24.590
There's a lot of research
taking place.

00:18:24.590 --> 00:18:29.020
The Army's partnering with a lot
of academic/medical communities

00:18:29.020 --> 00:18:32.080
because we want to
understand this better.

00:18:32.080 --> 00:18:37.410
And I think that the
stigma is changing.

00:18:37.410 --> 00:18:39.430
But the more I think about this --

00:18:39.430 --> 00:18:42.580
we've been focused on trying to get
behavioral health, behavioral care,

00:18:42.580 --> 00:18:45.880
further out into operational
units so it's more accessible.

00:18:45.880 --> 00:18:48.360
Someone doesn't have
to walk to the corner

00:18:48.360 --> 00:18:50.550
of an installation to get help.

00:18:50.550 --> 00:18:52.740
But it's just there.

00:18:52.740 --> 00:18:56.470
But I think we need to further
radically shape the paradigm

00:18:56.470 --> 00:19:00.470
which is not -- we're going to
provide care if you need it,

00:19:00.470 --> 00:19:03.060
but you're going to need
care when you come back.

00:19:03.060 --> 00:19:08.560
What we ask soldiers to
do on a regular basis,

00:19:08.560 --> 00:19:10.330
deployment after deployment,

00:19:10.330 --> 00:19:14.340
goes against how we're hardwired
biologically as human beings.

00:19:14.340 --> 00:19:17.290
And so it shouldn't be it's there
if you need it, and we're going

00:19:17.290 --> 00:19:18.590
to make it easy for you to find it.

00:19:18.590 --> 00:19:21.930
It should be you're going
to need it and you're going

00:19:21.930 --> 00:19:23.320
to get it when you come back.

00:19:23.320 --> 00:19:26.600
It should just be a part
of the cycle we have,

00:19:26.600 --> 00:19:29.680
much like how we maintain
tanks, for example.

00:19:29.680 --> 00:19:32.500
If we run them hard, we bring
them back, we strip them down,

00:19:32.500 --> 00:19:34.480
we put them back together.

00:19:34.480 --> 00:19:38.420
The Special Operations Command
has actually done a lot of work

00:19:38.420 --> 00:19:39.890
in this that's very interesting.

00:19:39.890 --> 00:19:44.170
But I think in 10/15/20 years we're
going to look back on this time

00:19:44.170 --> 00:19:45.970
and say wow, we really
missed a lot of things,

00:19:45.970 --> 00:19:47.270
got a lot of things wrong.

00:19:47.270 --> 00:19:50.080
And hopefully we'll have an
entire different way of looking

00:19:50.080 --> 00:19:53.690
at behavior health that --

00:19:53.690 --> 00:19:57.000
I would be frightened
to think we had an army

00:19:57.000 --> 00:19:58.860
of people doing what we ask of them

00:19:58.860 --> 00:20:01.110
and they're not impacted
by that mission.

00:20:01.110 --> 00:20:05.200
I don't even want to know
what that would look like.

00:20:05.200 --> 00:20:08.570
I wouldn't want to let that
loose on an adversary someplace,

00:20:08.570 --> 00:20:10.450
particularly its environments
we're talking about.

00:20:10.450 --> 00:20:12.150
And so I think we need to --

00:20:12.150 --> 00:20:14.860
I think we're in the process
of looking at this differently.

00:20:14.860 --> 00:20:16.270
But a lot more work has to be done.

00:20:16.270 --> 00:20:18.780
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: I want
to ask you a few questions,

00:20:18.780 --> 00:20:22.120
two questions about
women in the Army.

00:20:22.120 --> 00:20:23.420
Can you give us an update?

00:20:23.420 --> 00:20:27.110
Where are we with the expansion
of women into all roles

00:20:27.110 --> 00:20:29.490
in the Army including combat roles?

00:20:29.490 --> 00:20:33.290
And where do you see the
challenges in that transformation

00:20:33.290 --> 00:20:35.220
and that change for the Army?

00:20:35.220 --> 00:20:38.610
And then, secondly, an issue that's
gotten a lot of attention her

00:20:38.610 --> 00:20:41.490
on Capitol Hill in
the past several years

00:20:41.490 --> 00:20:44.910
which is sexual assault
in the military.

00:20:44.910 --> 00:20:48.560
What steps have been taken under
your watch as Secretary of the Army

00:20:48.560 --> 00:20:50.400
to try to solve that problem?

00:20:50.400 --> 00:20:53.650
&gt;&gt; Eric Fanning: So on the
first, women in combat --

00:20:53.650 --> 00:20:56.850
I think things are going very well.

00:20:56.850 --> 00:20:59.720
You know I always brag on the Army
on this one because I can do it

00:20:59.720 --> 00:21:02.820
without -- because it's -- a lot
of great work was done before I got

00:21:02.820 --> 00:21:07.570
to the Army to really analyze
what requirements are necessary

00:21:07.570 --> 00:21:09.720
to do all the jobs across the Army.

00:21:09.720 --> 00:21:14.740
And they are independent of
any qualifier of who you are.

00:21:14.740 --> 00:21:19.280
They're real requirements based
on the equipment, the mission.

00:21:19.280 --> 00:21:23.700
And then opening it up [inaudible]
to meet those requirements.

00:21:23.700 --> 00:21:29.310
We made a decision in the Army to
build the leadership cadre first,

00:21:29.310 --> 00:21:35.470
so to get new young lieutenants
in, to get enlisted, to re-branch,

00:21:35.470 --> 00:21:37.800
you know, who have had
some experience so that

00:21:37.800 --> 00:21:41.740
when we get brand new junior
soldiers in we've got leadership

00:21:41.740 --> 00:21:45.270
in place to help make the
transition as smooth as possible.

00:21:45.270 --> 00:21:49.260
And so the challenge, if you even
use that word "challenge" is just

00:21:49.260 --> 00:21:50.850
that it was going to
take a little bit of time

00:21:50.850 --> 00:21:52.750
to get some critical
mass going in there.

00:21:52.750 --> 00:21:55.000
But I think it's going very well.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:59.770
We see -- the women that I see,
they're at the vanguard of this,

00:21:59.770 --> 00:22:01.690
would be the people I'd
want fighting with me

00:22:01.690 --> 00:22:04.740
if I were wearing a uniform
in the army right now.

00:22:04.740 --> 00:22:06.210
They are impressive.

00:22:06.210 --> 00:22:07.900
They're dedicated.

00:22:07.900 --> 00:22:10.490
And they, more than anybody
else, want to make sure

00:22:10.490 --> 00:22:15.260
that the requirements are set and
that they meet the requirements.

00:22:15.260 --> 00:22:16.560
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Mm-hmm.

00:22:16.560 --> 00:22:17.860 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Eric Fanning: And sexual assault?

00:22:17.860 --> 00:22:21.030
Yeah, I think -- you know,
there were a lot of titles

00:22:21.030 --> 00:22:22.630
that were mentioned
in my introductions.

00:22:22.630 --> 00:22:25.090
Some of them were at the same time,

00:22:25.090 --> 00:22:28.890
but I've had nine different
jobs in this Administration.

00:22:28.890 --> 00:22:33.860
And so I've seen this from every
single corner of the Pentagon.

00:22:33.860 --> 00:22:36.550
And I do think it's been a --
it's been something we'll spend --

00:22:36.550 --> 00:22:38.260
I wouldn't say it's
been a priority of mine.

00:22:38.260 --> 00:22:40.920
It's been a priority of ours to
focus on this and get this right.

00:22:40.920 --> 00:22:44.860
It's critical that we get
at this and that we --

00:22:44.860 --> 00:22:48.000
you know, we are held to a higher
standard, and we should be.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:49.580
And we need to meet
that higher standard.

00:22:49.580 --> 00:22:53.530
And I think where my focus has been
in the last year with the Army,

00:22:53.530 --> 00:22:55.700
the last year plus, has been --

00:22:55.700 --> 00:22:59.460
we have done a lot on
the response aspect,

00:22:59.460 --> 00:23:02.150
making sure that lawyers are
changed, judges are changed.

00:23:02.150 --> 00:23:04.290
We have victims' advocates.

00:23:04.290 --> 00:23:09.190
But we need to make that
whole aspect irrelevant

00:23:09.190 --> 00:23:10.550
by getting at the prevention part.

00:23:10.550 --> 00:23:14.700
And that's been really my focus
the last 18 months as I've moved

00:23:14.700 --> 00:23:19.690
through the Army jobs as investing
in that part of our organization,

00:23:19.690 --> 00:23:23.240
pushing the team on the
research and on programs to get

00:23:23.240 --> 00:23:25.200
at the prevention part
which is harder.

00:23:25.200 --> 00:23:27.330
But I think we're making
some progress there.

00:23:27.330 --> 00:23:28.630
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Terrific.

00:23:28.630 --> 00:23:30.850
Well, if you hadn't
noticed, in the past couple

00:23:30.850 --> 00:23:34.640
of weeks we had a Presidential
Election and I --

00:23:34.640 --> 00:23:38.930
you know, I think it was a very
divisive Presidential Election.

00:23:38.930 --> 00:23:42.340
And one of the, I think,
good results out of it is

00:23:42.340 --> 00:23:44.700
that people are trying
to stay positive

00:23:44.700 --> 00:23:48.100
in their personal interactions
with each other and also online

00:23:48.100 --> 00:23:51.500
and social media, so I want to ask
a very positive question of you.

00:23:51.500 --> 00:23:54.370
I've been asking you a
lot of hard questions.

00:23:54.370 --> 00:23:57.340
We're going to celebrate
Thanksgiving in two days,

00:23:57.340 --> 00:24:00.580
so what are you most
thankful for this year?

00:24:00.580 --> 00:24:02.900
&gt;&gt; Eric Fanning: Well,
my [inaudible] --

00:24:02.900 --> 00:24:06.120
my answer to that is
the traditional one.

00:24:06.120 --> 00:24:10.780
But I felt it acutely over the
course of the last couple of years

00:24:10.780 --> 00:24:13.460
with confirmation processes and
movements and what have you.

00:24:13.460 --> 00:24:15.400 position:56%
And that's my friends and my family.

00:24:15.400 --> 00:24:20.030
I had -- you know, two years
ago now I was Undersecretary

00:24:20.030 --> 00:24:21.330
of the Air Force.

00:24:21.330 --> 00:24:22.860
The Secretary of the Air
Force is one of my oldest,

00:24:22.860 --> 00:24:24.450
closest, dearest friends.

00:24:24.450 --> 00:24:26.110
She worked on the House
Armed Services Committee

00:24:26.110 --> 00:24:28.690
with me, and just loving life.

00:24:28.690 --> 00:24:33.310
And Ash Carter, who I've known
for 25 years, came knocking

00:24:33.310 --> 00:24:37.260
and sets off a 12-month period
where I'm in five different jobs

00:24:37.260 --> 00:24:42.360
as I moved from the Air Force to
him to the Number Two in the Army

00:24:42.360 --> 00:24:45.110
to the Acting Secretary of the
Army, then back to his office

00:24:45.110 --> 00:24:48.160
because of the vagaries of
the confirmation process.

00:24:48.160 --> 00:24:52.560
And if I didn't have that sort
of stability in those touchpoints

00:24:52.560 --> 00:24:57.260
in my personal life it would have
been a much different 12 months.

00:24:57.260 --> 00:24:59.620
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Well, you
have just a tremendous resume.

00:24:59.620 --> 00:25:04.190
You've sat in all these very
impressive seats in the Pentagon.

00:25:04.190 --> 00:25:06.760
Can I ask you, what's
next in your career?

00:25:06.760 --> 00:25:08.290
What are the next steps?

00:25:08.290 --> 00:25:12.450 position:56%
And where do you think your skills
will be best utilized in the future?

00:25:12.450 --> 00:25:15.220
&gt;&gt; Eric Fanning: Well, I,
you know, I think I have one

00:25:15.220 --> 00:25:16.710
of the greatest jobs in the world

00:25:16.710 --> 00:25:19.430
that very few people
really understand the role

00:25:19.430 --> 00:25:23.030
of the Service Secretary which
is one of the reasons it's

00:25:23.030 --> 00:25:25.610
such a great job, because
they kind of leave you alone.

00:25:25.610 --> 00:25:28.880
Generally, if you get a call,
it's -- something bad has happened

00:25:28.880 --> 00:25:30.180
and you got to deal with it.

00:25:30.180 --> 00:25:33.770
But the autonomy that you get
as Service Secretary is great.

00:25:33.770 --> 00:25:38.300
And the way I describe it is
being the CEO of a business unit.

00:25:38.300 --> 00:25:40.280
I mean, I'm the CEO of the Army.

00:25:40.280 --> 00:25:44.380
The Army is a unbelievably
lethal war-fighting machine

00:25:44.380 --> 00:25:45.920
and a tool of national power.

00:25:45.920 --> 00:25:49.240
The Department of the Army is a
business unit that creates it.

00:25:49.240 --> 00:25:53.790 position:56%
And it's -- and so when I -- and the
confirmation process now having gone

00:25:53.790 --> 00:25:59.580
through it twice -- it takes a lot
out of people who go through it.

00:25:59.580 --> 00:26:02.100
And I had it relatively easy
compared to a lot of people.

00:26:02.100 --> 00:26:06.420
And so I said when I get through
this and get into this job

00:26:06.420 --> 00:26:09.730
that I love so much, I'm
going to focus on that job

00:26:09.730 --> 00:26:11.920
until they drag me
out of the building.

00:26:11.920 --> 00:26:16.350
And then I'm going to take a long
break someplace warm and then think

00:26:16.350 --> 00:26:18.140
about what it is I want to do next.

