you'd get more out of your budget,

00:39:15.400 --> 00:39:18.250
out of your program, I think,
than the way we manage now

00:39:18.250 --> 00:39:21.860
where there's no predictability,

00:39:21.860 --> 00:39:25.440
there's no reliability
to the budget.

00:39:25.440 --> 00:39:28.400
You can't manage the
Department of Defense

00:39:28.400 --> 00:39:31.570
on a series of 12-month cycles.

00:39:31.570 --> 00:39:34.330 position:56%
You certainly -- you know, it's very
difficult to manage in our series

00:39:34.330 --> 00:39:36.240
of three-month and
then nine-month cycles.

00:39:36.240 --> 00:39:37.860
And now we're going to get
a continuing resolution

00:39:37.860 --> 00:39:41.530
that takes us in, you know,
probably into six months.

00:39:41.530 --> 00:39:44.440
That costs a lot of
money to govern that way.

00:39:44.440 --> 00:39:46.820
And people don't understand
the impacts.

00:39:46.820 --> 00:39:50.650
This will be the first
administrative transition

00:39:50.650 --> 00:39:52.810
under a continuing resolution.

00:39:52.810 --> 00:39:56.920
And what a -- and people --
my predecessor, John McHugh,

00:39:56.920 --> 00:39:58.530
was a Member of Congress
for many years.

00:39:58.530 --> 00:39:59.900
And he said he thought
a CR was a good thing

00:39:59.900 --> 00:40:01.380
because it kept the spigot open.

00:40:01.380 --> 00:40:04.720
Well, all it does is let you
spend what you spent last year.

00:40:04.720 --> 00:40:06.890
So if you've got any new
program in your budget,

00:40:06.890 --> 00:40:09.480
you're not authorized
to spend on it.

00:40:09.480 --> 00:40:10.780
What does that do to your people?

00:40:10.780 --> 00:40:12.080
What does it do to contracts?

00:40:12.080 --> 00:40:13.380
What does it do to
the industrial brace.

00:40:13.380 --> 00:40:17.580
It adds costs year after
year after year to operate

00:40:17.580 --> 00:40:20.510
in such fiscal confusion.

00:40:20.510 --> 00:40:22.450
And I -- to me, that's
a big part of it.

00:40:22.450 --> 00:40:27.320
Now, the 25-year period,
the Berlin Wall falls,

00:40:27.320 --> 00:40:29.730
we took a knee a little bit
because you decide, okay,

00:40:29.730 --> 00:40:33.980
the world is stable enough that
I can take a little bit of risk

00:40:33.980 --> 00:40:36.060
and invest in something different.

00:40:36.060 --> 00:40:39.000
We haven't been able to do
that these last 15 or 20 years.

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:41.960
We haven't had -- we haven't been
able to take that balance where,

00:40:41.960 --> 00:40:45.360
okay, we've got a little
bit less risk geopolitically

00:40:45.360 --> 00:40:47.960
so we can take some risks
in being ready in order

00:40:47.960 --> 00:40:50.050
to invest in modernization.

00:40:50.050 --> 00:40:52.500
And you kind of balance
that out over these curves

00:40:52.500 --> 00:40:54.380
in a 25-or-longer-year period.

00:40:54.380 --> 00:40:56.140
So we haven't had that.

00:40:56.140 --> 00:40:59.780
And we've had -- we start --

00:40:59.780 --> 00:41:02.760
we end every fiscal year
preparing for a shutdown.

00:41:02.760 --> 00:41:05.830
A very inefficient
operation environment

00:41:05.830 --> 00:41:09.270
for the military the
last eight years.

